Lab 15: Transformations

Tyler Scott

2015-08-16

Goals for Today

  1. Perform (and understand) basic transformations

  2. Compare transformed and untransformed models

  3. Gain intuition about why/when to transform

  4. Standardize and interpret standardized variables

For todays lab, we will use the dataset of Michael Ross, Does Oil Hinder Democracy? World Politics, 2001. That paper estimated a time series cross-section model of Polity scores regressed on oil exports and a battery of controls.

library("dplyr")
library("ggplot2")
rossdata_url <- "http://staff.washington.edu/csjohns/503/rossoildata.csv"
rossdata_raw <- read.csv(rossdata_url, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
rossdata <- rossdata_raw %>%
  select(cty_name, year, regime1, oil, GDPcap, oecd) %>%
  na.omit()
  1. Lets run the standard model from Ross for the relationship between oil and GDP.
model1 <- lm(regime1 ~ GDPcap + oil + oecd + year, data = rossdata)

  1. Now predict the expected value of regime type vs.oil, for non-OECD countries with mean GDP per-capita and median year.

In order to interpret the interaction term graphically, we need to pick one variable to treat as continuous the x-axis and another for which we will choose specific values. Use oil as the x-axis, and some values of year at which to evaluate it. For year we could use the min, max, and median.

pred3_newdata <- expand.grid(oecd = 0,
                             GDPcap = mean(rossdata$GDPcap),
                             year = c(1966, 1981, 1997),
                             oil = seq(0, 100, by = 10))
pred3 <- predict(model3, newdata = pred3_newdata, interval = "confidence")
pred3 <- cbind(pred3,pred3_newdata)

Now, lets plot it,

ggplot(pred3, aes(x = oil, y = fit,
                  ymin = lwr,
                  ymax = upr,
                  colour = factor(year),fill=factor(year))) +
  geom_line() + geom_ribbon(alpha=0.2) +
  scale_colour_discrete("year")

First Differences

A common way of comparing the effect of a variable is to compare the results on \(\hat{y}\) for a variable at its mean and at its mean plus one standard deviation, holding all other variables at their means (if continuous), and their

year_seq <- seq(min(rossdata$year), max(rossdata$year), by = 1)
oil_lo <- mean(rossdata$GDPcap)
oil_hi <- mean(rossdata$GDPcap) + sd(rossdata$GDPcap)
pred3_oil_lo <-
  predict(model3,
          newdata = data.frame(year = year_seq,
                               GDPcap = mean(rossdata$GDPcap), 
                               oil = oil_lo,
                               oecd = 0),
          interval = "confidence")

pred3_oil_hi <-
  predict(model3,
          newdata = data.frame(year = year_seq,
                               GDPcap = mean(rossdata$GDPcap), 
                               oil = oil_hi,
                               oecd = 0),
          interval = "confidence")

The first difference is calculated. Note that there are no standard error associated with these differences.

pred3_diff <- data.frame(year = year_seq,
                         diff = pred3_oil_hi[ , "fit"] - pred3_oil_lo[ , "fit"])
head(pred3_diff)
##   year      diff
## 1 1966 -259.0802
## 2 1967 -271.1370
## 3 1968 -283.1938
## 4 1969 -295.2507
## 5 1970 -307.3075
## 6 1971 -319.3643

We could plot these differences over time.

ggplot(pred3_diff, aes(x = year, y = diff)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "red") +
  scale_y_continuous("Change in democracy")

Transformations

What if we suspect the effect of oil is non-linear?

Specifying a model:

model4 <- lm(regime1 ~ GDPcap + oil + I(oil^2) + oecd, data = rossdata)
summary(model4)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = regime1 ~ GDPcap + oil + I(oil^2) + oecd, data = rossdata)

## Residuals:

## F-statistic:   438 on 4 and 2589 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
oil_hyp <- seq(from = 0.01, to = 100, by = 10)
pred4 <- predict(model4,
                 newdata = data.frame(oil = oil_hyp,
                                      GDPcap = mean(rossdata$GDPcap),
                                      oecd = 0),
                 interval = "confidence") %>%
  as.data.frame()
pred4$oil <- oil_hyp

Plotting the resulting expectations:

ggplot(pred4, aes(x = oil)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = fit)) + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymax = upr, ymin = lwr), alpha = 1/3) +
  labs(x = "Percent oil", y = "Expected level of democracy", title = "Relationship of oil and democracy, with quadratic transformation of oil")

  1. Why was median used there?

We use the median here because it doesnt really make sense to think about average years.

  1. Plot the resulting expectations:
ggplot(pred.logGDP, aes(x = gdp)) +

  1. Transform oil by log. What happens? How would you solve it?
library(magrittr)
rossdata %>% mutate(l.oil = log(oil)) %>% summary(.$l.oil)

Log of 0 is undefined. This is often handled by adding and arbitrary small value to 0s. In this case well add 0.001. There are better ways to deal with this, but for now

model5 <- lm(regime1 ~ GDPcap + log(oil_mod) + oecd,
             data = mutate(rossdata, oil_mod = log(oil + 0.001)))
## Warning in log(oil_mod): NaNs produced
summary(model5)

Post-estimation Diagnostics

Recall the default model,

model1
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = regime1 ~ GDPcap + oil + oecd + year, data = rossdata)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       GDPcap          oil         oecd         year  
##  -1.736e+02    6.177e-05   -8.262e-02    4.116e+00    9.008e-02

Extract residuals and fitted values from an lm object:

result.vals = data.frame(residuals = model1$residuals,fitted = model1$fitted.values,outcome = rossdata$regime1,std.resids = rstandard(model1))
  1. Plot the fitted values vs.the outcome variable to look for nonlinearity,
ggplot(result.vals, aes(y = fitted,x = outcome)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  ylab("E(Democracy | X)") +
  xlab("Democracy")
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is >=1000, so using gam with formula: y ~ s(x, bs = "cs"). Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

and the residuals vs.the fitted values to look for heteroskedasticity

ggplot(result.vals, aes(x = fitted, y = residuals)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "red") + 
  ylab("Residual") +
  xlab("E(Democracy | X)")

  1. For model 1, plot residuals against each independent variable and the fitted values. Is there evidence of heteroskedasticity or nonlinearity?
results = data.frame(residuals = model1$residuals,fitted = model1$fitted.values,std.resids = rstandard(model1),rossdata)
plot(fitted~regime1,results)

Eh, doesnt look super bad, but not great either.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(std.resids~GDPcap,results)
abline(h=2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=-2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=0,lty=2)
plot(std.resids~oil,results)
abline(h=2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=-2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=0,lty=2)
plot(std.resids~oecd,results)
abline(h=2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=-2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=0,lty=2)
plot(std.resids~year,results)
abline(h=2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=-2,lty=2,col='red');abline(h=0,lty=2)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Definitely heteroskedasticity, with regards to both GDP per-capita and oil (in both cases, high variance at low levels and low variance at high levels)

  1. What about the normality of errors?
ggplot(results, aes(sample = std.resids)) + 
  stat_qq() + 
  geom_abline(slope = 1)
